  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 5682a2e0cbc484744981b7236e70439b, type: 3}
  m_Name: DataCenterWaterClippings
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  setId: datacenter_water_clippings
  setTitle: Recovered Records - Hunger Strike
  articles:
  - id: qts_georgia
    headline: "Town Told to Save Water \u2014 While a Data Center Secretly Took 29
      Million Gallons"
    date: May 2026
    body: "Residents in a Fayette County, Georgia neighborhood noticed the water
      pressure in their homes dropping. Officials told them to stop watering their
      lawns to conserve water. But the lawns were never the problem.\n\nA nearby
      data center had been quietly drawing about 29 million gallons of water through
      two pipe connections the county didn't even know existed \u2014 one installed
      without permission, the other never billed. That's roughly 44 swimming pools,
      used during a drought, while families were being asked to cut back.\n\nThe
      site is owned by one of the world's largest investment firms. After the secret
      usage came to light, the county billed the company for the missing water but
      chose not to fine it. The public only learned the truth when a resident obtained
      the county's letter and posted it online."
    sourceName: Tom's Hardware
    sourceUrl: https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/georgia-data-center-used-29-million-gallons-of-water
  - id: uruguay_google
    headline: A Nation Drank Salt Water as a Data Center Was Promised Millions of
      Gallons
    date: 2023
    body: "Uruguay was gripped by its worst drought in 74 years. The reservoirs fell
      so low that the government began mixing seawater into the public supply just
      to keep the taps running. The water turned salty and nearly undrinkable \u2014
      officials warned pregnant women and the seriously ill not to drink it at all.\n\nAround
      half a million people couldn't afford to buy bottled water instead. And through
      all of it, plans pushed forward for a Google data center that would eventually
      use millions of liters a day \u2014 as much water as 55,000 people.\n\nProtesters
      filled the streets of the capital and wrote a single sentence across its walls:
      \"It's not drought, it's pillage.\""
    sourceName: One Green Planet
    sourceUrl: https://www.onegreenplanet.org/environment/uruguayans-protest-googles-plan-use-water-drought/
  - id: queretaro_mexico
    headline: '"We Don''t Want Data Centers, We Want Water"'
    date: 2025
    body: "The state of Quer\xE9taro in central Mexico suffered its worst drought
      in a century. Seventeen of its eighteen municipalities were hit, and drinking
      water access was put at risk for thousands of families.\n\nThen came the announcement:
      32 new data centers planned for the same region. Residents gathered outside
      the facilities holding handmade signs with one plain demand \u2014 \"we don't
      want data centers, we want water.\""
    sourceName: Mongabay
    sourceUrl: https://news.mongabay.com/2025/11/ai-data-center-revolution-sucks-up-worlds-energy-water-materials/
  - id: mesa_meta
    headline: One Building. The Daily Water of 49,000 People. In the Desert.
    date: 2025
    body: "Arizona is one of the most water-stressed states in America, and the Colorado
      River it depends on drops lower every year.\n\nIn the city of Mesa, a single
      Meta data center secured an agreement allowing it to use up to 4 million gallons
      of water every day. That's about the same amount used by 49,000 people daily
      \u2014 running through one building, in the desert, to keep servers cool."
    sourceName: PANews
    sourceUrl: https://www.panewslab.com/en/articles/019e8624-79e0-7758-8b4e-7b466fea1872
  - id: utah_stratos
    headline: Nearly 4,000 People Paid to Object. Then the Application Disappeared.
    date: 2026
    body: "Beside the shrinking Great Salt Lake, in what locals called the worst
      drought in recorded history, a company proposed an enormous data center.\n\nNearly
      3,900 residents filed formal objections over the water it would consume \u2014
      and each person had to pay $15 just to file. Then the developer simply withdrew
      the application, which wiped out every one of those paid objections at once.
      The project kept moving forward anyway."
    sourceName: ZME Science
    sourceUrl: https://www.zmescience.com/ecology/climate/proposed-data-center-utah-heat/
  - id: global_total
    headline: 264,000,000,000 Gallons
    date: 2025
    body: "In one year, AI data centers drank roughly 264 billion gallons of water
      \u2014 about what 1.8 million people use in a year. Every single day, they
      consume around 550 million gallons, close to the entire output of the world's
      bottled water industry.\n\nAnd of 809 new data centers planned across the country,
      nearly two out of every three are slated for land already locked in drought.
      The thirstiest machines ever built, placed exactly where there is least water
      to give."
    sourceName: Barchart
    sourceUrl: https://www.barchart.com/story/news/2339834/ai-data-centers-water-consumption-breaks-264-billion-gallons-in-2025-as-devastating-drought-hits-nearly-63-of-u-s
